TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Design and Utilization of Communication Networks
AU  - Kalaba, R. E.
AU  - Juncosa, M. L.
Y1  - 1956/10/01
PY  - 1956
DA  - 1956/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.3.1.33
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.3.1.33
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 33
EP  - 44
VL  - 3
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - It is shown that a number of fundamental optimal routing and design problems for communication networks consisting of facilities for transmission, switching, relaying, etc., may be treated in a straightforward, computationally feasible manner by linear programming methods. These methods provide a general system approach for resolving the complex interactions among system capacities, users' demands, and economic factors. Various aspects of implementation and generalizations are discussed.
AB  - It is shown that a number of fundamental optimal routing and design problems for communication networks consisting of facilities for transmission, switching, relaying, etc., may be treated in a straightforward, computationally feasible manner by linear programming methods. These methods provide a general system approach for resolving the complex interactions among system capacities, users' demands, and economic factors. Various aspects of implementation and generalizations are discussed.
